captions.text:
MATT: Last season on Tuned
we drove the Switzer E900
Cornzilla GTR.

There were, of course, some
issues that came along with

the ridiculous amount of
horsepower that thing made.

Mainly, that it only ran on
ethanol, so you had to bring

your own fueling station
with you.

And the transmission, through
its upgrade, was a little

chattery, and not exactly what
we wanted for daily use.

Now, there's almost nothing
better than when either a

manufacturer or a tuner listens
to its customers and
upgrades cars accordingly.

And today, they have
sent us this.

It's the ultimate street edition
GTR, and it makes
1,000 horsepower on pump gas.

So I'm going to run up and
down the canyon a couple

times, and then we're going to
go to the flat part and see

where we can actually use
this crazy horsepower.

So what am I standing
here for?
[LOUD ENGINE NOISE]

There's nothing, really, that
says complete build like one
of Switzer's GTR packages.

You get a completely new engine
with forged rods,

pistons, crank, new cams, new
seals, all new cooling

equipment, trans and diff
equipment, new clutches.

So this car, although it's a
2009, all the running gear is
basically brand new.

So it's sort of like
having a new car.

The one downside I can see
to this is the price.

The package is $86,000,
plus your GTR.

So, considering you can get an
'09 for about $60,000, right?

For $140,000, you can get 880
wheel horsepower on pump gas,

or, like this car as it
right now, 962 wheel
horsepower on race gas.
[ENGINE REVS]

This one has Alcon rotors,
upgraded pads,
stainless steel lines.

The sizes of the rotors are
stock because they're about as

big as you can fit in
the wheels anyway.

But with the upgraded the
hardware, you should be able

to stop harder, more repeatedly,
getting less fade.

Because this is a heavy car,
so braking is key.
[ENGINE REVS]
Oh, yeah!
Oowee doggie!

That puts down some
power, doesn't it?
It is laggy.

It feels a little faster than
stock below 4,000 RPM.

Above 4,000 RPM, it's not an
amazing sound from in the cab.
Wow.

The back dances around, but the
front keeps you in line.
[ENGINE REVS]

It's fighting for traction
at the back.

Nobody will really accuse a flat
black Switzer GTR of not
looking cool.

But when I saw the exhaust tips,
I said something's not
right about that.
They stick too far out.

Then I asked why they
stick that far out.

It's because when the car shoots
fire, you don't want to
burn the bumper.

And all of a sudden,
it makes sense.

Now, traction, suspension, and
diff are all in R mode, so

when I hit it, even if the
rears break traction, it
shouldn't cut power.
[REVS ENGINE SHARPLY]
And it doesn't.
It doesn't.

The owner says he got 19 miles
per gallon driving this car

down to LA for me from
San Francisco.

But if the fuel gauge is
believed, then in three runs

up and down the canyon, I have
used a quarter of a tank.
Sorry.
[ENGINE REVS]

JUSTIN: We wanted to get a
package that basically wasn't

super loud, that was quiet, that
you can daily drive, and

basically is still a
beast on the track.

They built this specifically
around the street.

Everything has to
be functional.
It has to be reliable.
And I wanted that.
I wanted the reliability.

And ultimately, Switzer
delivered the best customer
service I've ever had.

I actually had an AMS
Alpha 6 before this.

Neil was constantly helping
me, even when it
wasn't their brand.
I love their company.

MATT: So your interior has an
interesting modification of
the back seat.
Explain the seat mod.

JUSTIN: Yeah, the backseat mod
saves about one pound.

MATT: Can anyone
sit back there?
JUSTIN: They can.
I'm don't suggest they do.

MATT: Power figures
are ridiculous.

There are actually people out
there who will watch this
video and go, meh.
962 at the wheels.
That's not fast.

I saw a video of a car
that did this.
Yeah, come drive this thing.
962 isn't fast.
This thing is stupid fast.
Alright.
Too much car, not enough road.

We need to go find a couple
straightaways.

What's your favorite thing
about the GTR in general?
JUSTIN: In general?
Launching it.
MATT: He told me to launch it.
So, a 1,000 horsepower launch.
Here we go.
[ENGINE REVS]
Holy shit.
Whoa!
[ENGINE ROARS]
Wow-wa-wa-wa!

That's why people drive
1,000 horsepower GTRs.
To do that.

Well the launch is
properly crazy.

Let's see what happens
when I have grip.

I'll do a second gear
roll-on here.
[ENGINE REVS]
That was pretty impressive.
Let's try it again.
[ENGINE REVS]
[INAUDIBLE]
[ENGINE ROARS]

I'm not going to tell you how
fast that was, because even

though this road belongs
to us, trust me.
You don't want to know.
But damn.

How about a first
gear roll-on.
[ENGINE REVS]

First gear is basically
nonexistent.

By the time you get into boost,
you're already bouncing
off the rev limiter.

Alright, how about a roll-on
from third gear.
Flat, it's going, now--
[INAUDIBLE]
[ENGINE ROARS]

And if one day you decided you
were having a bad day, you
could just--
[ENGINE REVS]

We end at a gas station here
in Camarillo, where we

remember the true beauty
of this car.

The last time we drove a Switzer
car, we had to carry

jugs of ethanol just to
get the thing home.

But we're here, with
a regular pump.

And after driving around all
day doing poles, running

canyons, I'm going to fill this
thing up with 91 octane.

And these guys are going to get
in it and drive back to
San Francisco.

It doesn't have race
gas, just pump.

So they're only going to have
880 wheel horsepower instead

of the 962 I've been able
to play with all day.

20 years ago, this kind of power
would've required a race
team, a trailer--
who even knows.

And now he can just get in it,
type in his home address, fill

it with pump gas, turn on the
radio, turn on the air

conditioning, and he's
home just like that.
It's the best thing ever.

I'd like to thank Justin for
bringing me his car today, and

Neil Switzer for building it,
something so completely

ridiculous and still
somehow usable.

And until next time, for our
season finale on Tuned, I'm
Matt Farah.

Follow me @TheSmokingTire
on Twitter.
Buy these shirts.
Driveshirts.com.
I'm done.

Maybe you don't like
your wife.
Maybe you'd prefer jail.

Maybe things aren't
going so good.

Call up Switzer,
and then just--
[ENGINE REVS]
Jail.

Four wheel burnout,
straight to jail.

Look at the accelerometer
graph.
Wow.

comments.text:
+TheS1PikesPeak Yeah that "bad fuel quality" thing is just a 
misunderstanding as a lot of people don't know about the different rating 
systems. As +Christopher Nord mentioned very accurately, the US uses the 
(R+M)/2 and Europe uses RON - there are actually several additional ways of 
measuring octane in fuel, including MON, AKI, and RdON.
So, I think when people in Europe, not knowing about the different ratings, 
saw that the premium fuel in the US was 91 and Europe's premium fuel had a 
higher number of 98, the rumor began that the quality was worse here. It's 
a simple mistake to make. The rating system is quite complicated. Diesel 
fuel also has a rating system but, instead of octane, they rate the cetane 
in their fuel.

but other countries do that as well.  RON (European) vs (R+M)/2 (US) 
ratings are what we're talking about. My Ducati Hypermotard requires 95 RON 
per the manual, which is equivalent to our 89-90 (R+M)/2  "midgrade" gas. 
Premium, for motors that require it, is 91-93 here.
